> Though it may seem unusual, rosemary is a common addition to authentic Mexican chilies. Its warm, woodsy aroma makes this dish even more comforting than it already is. A few tablespoons of cornmeal makes this wintery white dish deliciously thick and creamy.

== Prep the Ingredients ==

Halve, peel, and dice the @yellow onion{4%ounce}. Strip the @rosemary{¼%ounce} and @oregano{¼%ounce} off the stems and finely chop the leaves. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Drain and rinse the @cannellini beans{1%box}.

== Start the Chili ==

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large #pot over medium heat. Add the onion to the #pot and cook, tossing, for ~{5-6%minutes}, until very soft. Add the garlic, oregano, and rosemary to the #pot and cook for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add the @ground turkey{8%ounce} to the #pot and cook, breaking up the meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through. Add the @cumin{1%teaspoon}, @smoked paprika{1%teaspoon}, and a pinch of @cayenne pepper{1%teaspoon} (to taste, we used ¼ teaspoon) to the #pot and cook for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Season with salt and pepper.

== Finish the Chili ==

Add @water{3%cups} and the @chicken stock concentrate{2%unit} to the #pot and stir to combine. Bring to a boil, then stir in @polenta{3%tablespoons} and the cannellini beans. Reduce the heat and simmer for ~{12-15%minutes}, until very thick. Taste and season with salt and pepper, if necessary.

Divide the chili between #bowls{}, then finish with a dollop of @sour cream{1%ounce}. Enjoy!